    <h2>
      CHAPTER III.
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">O</span>ne morning in
      August Mrs. Clarendon was sitting in the garden at Knightswell, with Ada
      Warren and a young lady named Rhoda Meres, a guest at the house. They had
      chosen a spot which was often resorted to for tea on hot afternoons, a
      little piece of lawn closely shut in with leafage, whence an overbowered
      pathway led out to the front garden. The lady of Knightswell sat
      reposefully in a round-backed rustic chair. She wore a pretty garden
      costume, a dainty web of shawl just covering her head, her crossed feet
      just showing below the folds of her dress. An open sunshade lay tumbled on
      the grass beside her, and on her lap was an illustrated paper, of which
      she turned the leaves with idle interest. Miss Warren sat a couple of
      yards away, reading a review. Her dress was plain, and of dark material,
      and she wore a brown broad-brimmed straw hat. The other young lady made no
      pretence of being occupied. With knit brows and bent head she walked
      backwards and forwards on the grass, biting a long leaf which she had
      pulled from a bough in passing. She was a pretty girl, fair-cheeked and
      graceful of form. She carried her hat by its ribbon, and let the stray
      sunlight make gleamings upon her golden hair. Her age was not quite
      nineteen, and the beautiful lines of her maiden figure lost nothing by her
      way of holding herself, whether she moved or stood.
    </p>
    <p>
      After several side glances at her silent companions, she presently came to
      a pause before Mrs. Clarendon&rsquo;s chair, and, still holding the leaf between
      her lips, asked, rather plaintively:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why shouldn&rsquo;t I, Mrs. Clarendon?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Isabel looked up with suave smiling features, and met the girl&rsquo;s eyes in
      silence for a moment.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;My dear Rhoda,&rdquo; she said then, &ldquo;why should you?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No,&rdquo; urged the girl, &ldquo;I think all the reasons are needed on the other
      side. I must do something, and this is what I think I&rsquo;m suited for. Why
      shouldn&rsquo;t I?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;For one thing, because you are a lady, and ladies don&rsquo;t do such things.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;There you have Mrs. Clarendon&rsquo;s last word,&rdquo; remarked Ada Warren, without
      looking up. Her voice contrasted strangely with those which had been just
      heard; it was hard in tone, giving clear utterance to each syllable, as if
      to accentuate the irony in her observation.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Certainly,&rdquo; said Isabel, with good humour; &ldquo;if Rhoda is content to let it
      be.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Still biting her leaf, Miss Meres held her head a little on one side, and,
      after glancing at Ada, turned her eyes again upon Mrs. Clarendon.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But are you quite sure it is so, Mrs. Clarendon?&rdquo; she urged. &ldquo;I mean that
      ladies don&rsquo;t go on to the stage? It used to be so, no doubt, but things
      have been changing. I&rsquo;m sure I&rsquo;ve heard that both ladies and gentlemen are
      beginning to take to acting nowadays. And I can&rsquo;t see why they shouldn&rsquo;t.
      It seems to be better than&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She stopped, and looked a little embarrassed.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Better than doing nothing at all, you were going to say,&rdquo; Isabel
      supplied; &ldquo;like myself, for instance? Perhaps it is. But I fancy that the
      ladies who go on to the stage are generally those who, for some reason or
      other, have lost their places in society.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;With a large S,&rdquo; put in Ada, still without looking up.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, a very large one,&rdquo; assented Isabel, smiling.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And suppose,&rdquo; exclaimed Rhoda, suddenly bold, &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t care anything
      about the society which spells itself with a large S.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Mrs. Clarendon shook her head indulgently.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;My child, you can&rsquo;t help caring about it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Not if I find something I like better outside it?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Mrs. Clarendon crossed her hands upon the paper, and sighed a little
      before speaking.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You think it would be nice to become a Bohemian, and live in contempt of
      us poor subjects of Mrs. Grundy. Rhoda, those Bohemians struggle for
      nothing so hard as to get into society. If they are successful, the best
      fruit of their success is an invitation to a lady&rsquo;s &lsquo;at home,&rsquo; the
      unsuccessful ones would give their ears to be received in the most
      commonplace little drawing-room. Now you have already what they strive for
      so desperately. You&rsquo;ll see all this plainly enough when you know a little
      more of the world.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Rhoda turned away, and recommenced her pacing.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What does your father say to it?&rdquo; Mrs. Clarendon asked, after a short
      silence.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Father? Oh! he shrugs his shoulders and looks puzzled. Poor father always
      does that, whatever the difficulty. If I ask him whether the butcher
      hasn&rsquo;t charged us too much a pound for veal, he shrugs and looks puzzled.
      I believe he&rsquo;d do just the same if I asked him whether to-morrow wasn&rsquo;t
      going to be the Day of Judgment.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Isabel raised her forefinger with a warning smile. Ada Warren laughed.
    </p>
    <p>
      After another turn on the grass, the girl again paused before Mrs.
      Clarendon.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Mr. Lacour told me the other day that he thought of going on to the stage
      himself. He didn&rsquo;t see any harm in it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      As she spoke, Rhoda examined the border of her hat.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Mr. Lacour!&rdquo; exclaimed Isabel. &ldquo;Oh, Mr. Lacour says wonderful things, and
      has wonderful plans. So you confided your project to Mr. Lacour, did you?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Isabel threw a rapid glance at Ada whilst speaking; the latter appeared
      busy with her book.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, no,&rdquo; disclaimed Rhoda rapidly, &ldquo;I didn&rsquo;t say a word to him of my own
      idea. It only came out in conversation.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Mrs. Clarendon gave a little &ldquo;h&rsquo;m,&rdquo; and stroked the back of one hand with
      the fingers of the other.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It&rsquo;s a mistake, my dear Rhoda,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;Like it or not, we have to
      consider our neighbour&rsquo;s opinion, and that doesn&rsquo;t yet regard the stage as
      a career open to gentlemen&rsquo;s daughters.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;There&rsquo;s no knowing what we <i>may</i> come to,&rdquo; remarked Ada absently.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Then what <i>am</i> I to do, Mrs. Clarendon?&rdquo; cried the other girl almost
      piteously.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;A great many things. To begin with, you have to help me to make my garden
      party on Monday a success. Then again&mdash;&mdash;oh, you have to become
      acquainted with my cousin, Mr. Asquith. Here he is!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      From the covered pathway issued a tall gentleman of middle age, dressed in
      a cool summer suit, holding his hat in his hands. His appearance was what
      is called prepossessing; by his own complete ease and air of genial
      well-being he helped to put others in the same happy state, his
      self-satisfaction not being of the kind which irritates by excess. His
      head was covered with a fine growth of black hair, which continued itself
      in the form of full whiskers, and with these blended the silken grace of a
      moustache long enough to completely conceal the lips. His features were
      slightly browned by Eastern suns. His eyes, as he viewed in turn each of
      the three ladies, had a calm, restful gaze which could have embarrassed no
      one, hinting only the friendliest of inward comment.
    </p>
    <p>
      Isabel rose and stepped forward to meet him. In the act of greeting she
      was, perhaps, seen to greatest advantage. The upright grace of her still
      perfect figure, the poise of her head, the face looking straight forward,
      the smile of exquisite frankness, the warmth of welcome and the natural
      dignity combined in her attitude as she stood with extended hand, made a
      picture of fair womanhood which the eye did not readily quit. It was
      symbolical of her inner self, of the large affections which made the air
      about her warm, and of the sweet receptiveness of disposition which
      allowed so many and so different men to see in her their ideal of a woman.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You found the trap at the station?&rdquo; she asked, and, satisfied on this
      point, presented him to her companions. Though Asquith had just reached
      England in time to see his cousin once or twice before she left London, he
      had still to become acquainted with Ada Warren, who did not go to town
      with Mrs. Clarendon, but preferred to make her visits at other times,
      staying with Mr. Meres and his daughters. Ada was silent during the
      ceremony of introduction, and did not give her hand; Rhoda showed her more
      expansive nature and smiled prettily in Robert&rsquo;s face.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I thought you would find it pleasant to come and sit here a little before
      lunch,&rdquo; said Isabel, by way of leading to conversation.
    </p>
    <p>
      But Asquith merely bent his head; he seemed all at once to have become a
      trifle absent, and, after letting his gaze rest on Miss Warren for a few
      moments, had turned his look groundwards. But the interval was very short.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That groom of yours who drove me over,&rdquo; he began, in a leisurely tone and
      with an appreciative smile, &ldquo;is a wonderful man.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That&rsquo;s interesting,&rdquo; said Isabel. &ldquo;I fear I haven&rsquo;t discovered his
      exceptional qualities.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;They are remarkable. His powers of observation. I make a point of
      conversing whenever opportunity offers. The suggestive incident was a pig
      crossing the road; I remarked that it was a fine pig. By a singular
      accident I must have hit upon the man&rsquo;s specialty; he looked at me with
      gratitude, and forthwith gave me&mdash;you can&rsquo;t imagine&mdash;the most
      wonderful disquisition on pigs. He spoke as if he loved them. &lsquo;Now, a
      pig&rsquo;s heye, sir! Did you ever happen to notice a pig&rsquo;s heye, sir?&rsquo; I was
      afraid to say that I had. &lsquo;There&rsquo;s more in a pig&rsquo;s heye, sir, than you&rsquo;d
      find creditable,&rsquo;&mdash;meaning credible, of course. &lsquo;There&rsquo;s that
      knowingness in a pigs heye, sir, it can&rsquo;t be described in words. <i>When</i>
      it isn&rsquo;t fierce,&mdash;and if it is, the fierceness of it there&rsquo;s no
      imagining!&rsquo;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      This narration, given with much quiet humour, made Mrs. Clarendon and
      Rhoda laugh. Ada Warren had resumed her review, or at all events had it
      lying open on her lap, and showed no smile. Robert watched her with his
      quiet eyes. In Miss Meres he seemed to have little interest, and he looked
      far more frequently at Ada than at Mrs. Clarendon.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;By-the-bye, some one we passed on the road,&rdquo; he said presently. He had a
      curious habit of mentioning in this disjointed way the subject of the
      remark he was about to make, and, so reposeful was his habit of speech, it
      often seemed as if the comment would never follow. &ldquo;A young man, rather
      good-looking, or perhaps, rather noticeable. My friend the groom told me
      he was a settler in these parts; a gentleman who has taken a labourer&rsquo;s
      cottage, and lives in a more or less eccentric way. It sounded
      interesting. Do you know anything of him?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh yes,&rdquo; said Isabel, &ldquo;our rector, Mr. Vissian, knows him, and speaks of
      him in superlatives. His name is Kingcote.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But what is he doing here?&mdash;reading, rusticating? I suppose he&rsquo;s
      taken the cottage just for the summer months?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Mr. Vissian says he has settled here for good&mdash;a philosopher, who is
      tired of town life. He comes from London. I haven&rsquo;t been favoured with a
      glimpse of him yet, but several people have spoken of him. I think I must
      ask Mr. Vissian to bring him here.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;A month or so of summer would be pleasant, spent in that way,&rdquo; observed
      Mr. Asquith; &ldquo;but to settle finally! Something morbid about him, I
      suppose; he looks, in fact, rather bloodless, like a man with a fixed
      idea. Ten to one, he&rsquo;s on precisely the wrong tack; instead of wanting
      more of his own society, he ought to have less of it. I suppose he lives
      alone?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Quite.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The worst thing for any man. I shouldn&rsquo;t dare to converse with myself
      exclusively for two consecutive days. The great, preservative of sanity is
      free intercourse with one&rsquo;s fellow men&mdash;to see the world from all
      points, and to refrain from final conclusions.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Chat of this kind went on for a few minutes, all taking part in it except
      Ada.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You are fond of the country, Miss Warren,&rdquo; Asquith said at length,
      addressing the latter directly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, I&rsquo;m fond of the country,&rdquo; was the reply, given in a mechanical way,
      and with a cold, steady look, whilst she ruffled the edges of her review.
      Asquith had found it at first difficult to determine whether the
      peculiarity of the girl&rsquo;s behaviour were due to excessive shyness or to
      some more specific cause; but shyness it certainly was not, her manner of
      speaking and of regarding him put that out of the question. Did she, then,
      behave in this way to every stranger, or was he for some reason personally
      distasteful to her; or, again, had something just happened to disturb her
      temper?
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Your liking for it, though, would scarcely go to the extent of leading
      you to take up a solitary abode in a labourers cottage?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I can&rsquo;t say,&rdquo; Ada replied slowly. &ldquo;One is often ready to do anything for
      the sake of being left alone.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ada would stipulate, however, to be supplied with the <i>Fortnightly</i>
      or the <i>Nineteenth Century</i>,&rdquo; put in Mrs. Clarendon laughingly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;If anything could drive me into the desert,&rdquo; was Robert&rsquo;s remark, &ldquo;it
      would be the hope of never again being called upon to look at them. I
      shouldn&rsquo;t wonder if Mr.&mdash;Mr. Kingcote, isn&rsquo;t it?&mdash;has fled from
      civilisation for the very same reason. Probably he has cast away books,
      and aims at returning to the natural state of man.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;By no means,&rdquo; said Isabel. &ldquo;He has brought down quite a library.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Alas!&rdquo; exclaimed Robert, with a humorous shaking of the head, &ldquo;then he
      is, I fear, engaged in adding to the burden which oppresses us. No wonder
      he hides his head; he is writing a book.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Perhaps he is a poet, Mrs. Clarendon,&rdquo; puts in Rhoda.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Perhaps so, Rhoda; and some day we may have pilgrims from all corners of
      the earth visiting the cottage he has glorified.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;With special omnibuses from Winstoke station,&rdquo; added Robert, &ldquo;and a
      colony of licensed victuallers thriving about the sacred spot.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Let us be thankful,&rdquo; exclaimed Isabel, &ldquo;that a poet&rsquo;s fame is usually
      deferred for a generation or two. Ha, there&rsquo;s the first luncheon bell! It
      brings a smile to your face, Robert.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Did I betray myself? I confess I breakfasted early.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The two girls walked towards the house together, their elders following
      more slowly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Isn&rsquo;t Rhoda Meres a nice girl?&rdquo; said Isabel, when the object of her
      remark was out of hearing.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Very,&rdquo; her cousin assented, though without enthusiasm. He seemed to be
      thinking of something else.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The poor child has got a foolish idea into her head; she wants to go on
      to the stage.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Does she&mdash;ha? Most young people have that idea at one time or
      another, I believe. In default of a special audience of one, you see&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And she <i>is</i> such a good, dear girl!&rdquo; pursued Isabel, when Asquith
      showed no sign of continuing. &ldquo;Her father is a literary man, the editor of
      a magazine called <i>Ropers Miscellany</i>&mdash;do you know it? He and I
      are the best of old friends. Its only with the thought of helping her
      father, I&rsquo;m sure, that Rhoda has taken up this fancy; we must drive it out
      of her head somehow.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, I suppose so,&rdquo; remarked Robert, more absently than before.
    </p>
    <p>
      Isabel glanced at him, and kept silence till they reached the house.
    </p>
    <p>
      There was nothing remarkable about the structure itself of Knightswell;
      the front was long and low, built of brick faced with stone, and the level
      entrance was anything but imposing. The main portion of the building was
      early eighteenth century, but in the rear there still existed a remnant of
      the sixteenth century manor-house which had once stood here; the ancient
      hall now served as kitchen, its fine stone fireplace being filled up with
      an incongruous modern range. The present hall was surrounded with oak
      panelling, which Mr. Clarendon had obtained at the dismantling of an old
      house in the neighbourhood; all else of the interior had become, by
      successive changes, completely modernised, with the exception of an
      elaborate chimney-piece in the drawing-room&mdash;massive marble-work
      resting on caryatides&mdash;always said, though without corroborative
      evidence, to be a production of Grinling Gibbons. The faces of the two
      supporters were curiously unlike each other: on the one side it was that
      of a youthful maiden, who smiled, and seemed to be upraising her arms in
      sport; the other was an aged but not unbeautiful face, wearing an
      expression of long-suffering sadness, worn under the burden which the
      striving arms sustained. In the dining-room were a few good pictures,
      taken with the house from the preceding occupants. For Knightswell was not
      the ancestral abode of Mr. Clarendon&rsquo;s family; it had passed, by frequent
      changes, from tenant to tenant, all inglorious. Notwithstanding his
      historic name, Mr. Clarendon was a <i>novus homo</i>; his father had begun
      life as an obscure stockbroker, had made a great fortune, and ended his
      life in a comfortable dwelling in Bayswater; his daughters, there were
      two, married reputably, and were no more heard of.
    </p>
    <p>
      During luncheon Asquith was still much occupied in observing Ada Warren
      whenever he could unobtrusively do so. The young ladies were rather
      silent, and even Isabel showed now and then a trace of effort in the
      bright flow of talk which she kept up. Between herself and her cousin,
      however, there was no lack of ease; a graceful intimacy had established
      itself on the basis of their kinship, though not exactly that kind of
      intimacy which bespeaks life-long association. Their talk was of the
      present, or of the immediate past; neither spoke of things or people whose
      mention would have revived the memory of years ago.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And what are you doing with yourself?&rdquo; Mrs. Clarendon inquired, when
      Robert had abandoned another futile attempt to draw Ada Warren into
      converse.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Upon my word,&rdquo; was his reply, &ldquo;I hardly know. The town; I see a good deal
      of it, indoors and out; it still has the charm of novelty. I can&rsquo;t say
      that time has begun to hang heavy on my hands; in truth, it seldom does.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Fortunate being!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, I suppose so. I find that people have a singular capacity for being
      bored; I notice it more than I used to. For my own part, I generally find
      a good deal of enjoyment to be got out of the present moment; the
      enjoyment of sound health, at lowest. You know how pleasant it is to look
      back on past days, even though at the time they may have seemed anything
      but delightful. I account for that by believing that the past always had a
      preponderant element of pleasure, though disturbing circumstances wouldn&rsquo;t
      allow us to perceive it. It&rsquo;s always a joy to be alive, and we recognise
      this in looking back, when accidents arrange themselves in their true
      proportion.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He glanced at Ada; the girl was smiling scornfully, her face averted to
      the window.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The present being so delightful,&rdquo; said Mrs. Clarendon, &ldquo;what joyous
      pleasures have you for the immediate future?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Grouse on Wednesday next,&rdquo; Robert replied, after helping himself to salt
      in a manner which suggested that he was observant of the number of grains
      he took. &ldquo;An acquaintance who has a moor, or a portion of one, in
      Yorkshire, has given me an invitation. As I have never shot grouse, I
      shall avail myself of the opportunity to extend my experience.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Promise me the pick of your first bag.&rdquo; There was a project for a long
      drive in the afternoon; the weather was bright but sufficiently cool, and
      Robert professed himself delighted. He had a few minutes by himself in the
      drawing-room when the ladies went up to make their preparations. He gave a
      careful scrutiny to the caryatides, smiling, as was generally the case
      when he regarded anything, then glanced about at the pictures and the
      chance volumes lying here and there; the latter were novels and light
      literature from Mudie&rsquo;s. Then he took up a number of the <i>Queen</i>, and
      began to peruse it, sitting in the window-seat.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What a singular choice of literature!&rdquo; exclaimed Isabel, as she came in
      drawing on her gloves.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The <i>Queen?</i> It interests me. There&rsquo;s something so very concrete
      about such writing. I like the concrete.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The first time I ever heard so learned a term applied to so frivolous a
      publication. After all, Rhoda, there may be more in us poor creatures than
      we gave ourselves credit for.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Do tell me,&rdquo; said Robert, as he laid down the paper, &ldquo;what is a&mdash;I
      hope I may ask&mdash;what is a &lsquo;graduated plastron&rsquo;?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, this is dreadful!&rdquo; laughed Isabel. &ldquo;Come along, the carriage is
      waiting; we&rsquo;ll discuss graduated plastrons on our way.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Are we not to have the pleasure of Miss Warren&rsquo;s company?&rdquo; Robert asked,
      as they entered the phaeton.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ada never goes out with us,&rdquo; was Mrs. Clarendon&rsquo;s answer as she took the
      reins and prepared to drive.
    </p>
    <p>
      There was no additional guest at dinner; the evening was helped along by
      Rhoda&rsquo;s playing and singing. Her voice was good, and she had enjoyed good
      teaching; this at Mrs. Clarendon&rsquo;s expense. It was one of many instances
      in which Isabel had helped her friends the Meres, her aid being given in a
      manner of which she alone had the secret&mdash;irresistible, warm-hearted,
      delicate beyond risk of offence. Ada sat in the room, but, as usual, had a
      book in her hands.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You read much,&rdquo; said Robert, seating himself beside her and perforce
      obtaining her attention.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It is a way of getting through life,&rdquo; the girl replied, rather less
      abruptly than she had hitherto spoken.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That means that life is not quite so attractive to you as it might be?&rdquo;
       he returned, under the cover of the music which had just begun.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I doubt whether life is attractive to any one&mdash;who thinks about it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She had folded her hands on the pages and was leaning back in her chair.
      Robert examined her and came to the conclusion that she was not quite so
      disagreeable in countenance as the irregularity of her features at first
      led one to think. She had large eyes, and, to meet them, was to be
      strangely impressed, almost as with the attraction of beauty. Her evening
      dress was of black satin, a richer and more tasteful garment than he had
      expected she would wear, judging from her appearance earlier in the day.
      Her hair, too, was very carefully arranged. The foot, which just showed
      itself, was not small, but beautifully shaped. Ornaments she had none.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That is censure clearly directed against myself,&rdquo; Robert said, with good
      humour. &ldquo;And yet I fancy I have thought a good deal of life.&rdquo; Ada did not
      seem disposed to pursue the argument.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What are you reading?&rdquo; Asquith inquired. It was a volume of Comte. She
      showed the title without speaking.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You are a Positivist?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No; merely an atheist.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The confession was uttered in such a matter-of-fact tone that Robert was
      disposed to think she used the word just for the pleasure of startling
      him. There was, in fact, a barely perceptible glimmer in her eyes as she
      sat looking straight before her.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That&rsquo;s rather dogmatic, isn&rsquo;t it?&rdquo; he remarked, smiling. &ldquo;The word
      Agnostic is better, I fancy.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I believe it comes to very much the same thing,&rdquo; said Ada. &ldquo;The new word
      has been coined principally to save respectability.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;A motive with which you have small sympathy?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;None whatever.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      There was a silence between them.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You play?&rdquo; Robert asked, Rhoda Meres having risen from the piano.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Only for my own amusement.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Then certainly you play things which I should like to hear. Will you play
      me something that has a tune in it? I don&rsquo;t mean to reflect upon Miss
      Meres&rsquo; playing; but my ear is in a rudimentary state. I should be very
      grateful if you would play something.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Ada seemed to harden her face against an intruding smile. She rose,
      however, and walked over to the piano. Mrs. Clarendon and Rhoda looked at
      her with undisguised surprise. Asquith noticed that her walk might have
      been graceful, had she not affected a sort of indifference in gait.
    </p>
    <p>
      She seated herself at the instrument and played an operatic air; it lasted
      about three minutes, then she ceased. Robert looked in expectation of her
      resuming her former seat, but she walked straight to the door and
      disappeared.
    </p>
    <p>
      Mrs. Clarendon and Rhoda Meres exchanged glances, and for an instant there
      was a rather awkward silence. Isabel found a subject, and talked with her
      wonted vivacity.
    </p>
    <p>
      Ada did not return. About half-past ten Rhoda began to make preparations
      for departure; she went to one of the windows, and held the blind aside a
      little to look out at the night.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh! what a moon!&rdquo; she exclaimed. &ldquo;Mrs. Clarendon, do let us just go out
      for a minute on to the lawn; the country is so wonderful at night.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Wrappers were at hand for the ladies, and the three went out together. The
      whole scope of visible heavens was pale with light; the blacker rose the
      circle of trees about Knights Well. The leaves made their weird
      whispering, each kind with its separate voice; no other sounds came from
      the sleeping earth.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We often hear the nightingale,&rdquo; Isabel said, lowering her voice. &ldquo;Perhaps
      it&rsquo;s too early yet.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Then she added:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;This is the hour of our poet&rsquo;s inspiration.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What poet?&rdquo; asked Robert.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Our poet in the cottage; don&rsquo;t you remember?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ah, the morbid young man. Poor fellow!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Isabel suppressed a low laugh.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Come, Rhoda dear, it&rsquo;s cold,&rdquo; she said to the girl, who had drawn a
      little apart.
    </p>
    <p>
      Rhoda followed in silence, her head bent. In the hall she took her candle,
      and bade the two a hasty good-night.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why is she crying?&rdquo; asked Robert, under his voice, as he entered the
      drawing-room again with Isabel.
    </p>
    <p>
      The latter shook her head, but did not speak. She moved about the room for
      a moment; the shawl had half slipped from her shoulders, and made a
      graceful draping. Asquith stood watching her.
    </p>
    <p>
      She approached him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I half hinted,&rdquo; she began, &ldquo;that I had a selfish object in asking you to
      come here. We are good friends, are we not?&mdash;old and good friends?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      There was a beautiful appeal upon her face, anxiety blending with a slight
      embarrassment. She had put aside the mask of light-heartedness, and that
      which it had all day been in her countenance to utter freely exposed
      itself. It was not so much as distress; rather, impatience of some
      besieging annoyance. She was more beautiful now than when Robert had read
      her face seventeen years ago. Still, he regarded her with his wonted
      smile. There was much kindness in his look; nothing more than kindness.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The best of friends, Isabel, I hope,&rdquo; he replied to her.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am going to ask you to do something for me,&rdquo; she continued. &ldquo;Will you
      sit down and listen to me? I am not sure that I do right in asking this
      favour of you, but you are the only one of my relatives whom I feel able
      to talk freely with, and I think I had rather you than any one else did
      this thing that I am going to ask. Perhaps you will find it too
      disagreeable; if so, tell me&mdash;you will promise to speak freely?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Certainly, I promise.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      They had taken their seats. Asquith rested one of his arms on a small
      table, and waited, the smile lingering. Isabel gathered the shawl about
      her, as if she felt cold. She was a trifle pale.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You understand perfectly,&rdquo; she resumed, with a certain abruptness, which
      came of the effort it cost her to broach the subject, &ldquo;the meaning of Ada
      Warren&rsquo;s presence in this house?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Perfectly, I think,&rdquo; her cousin replied, with a slight motion of his
      eyebrows.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That is to say,&rdquo; pursued Isabel, looking at the fringe of her shawl, &ldquo;you
      know the details of Mr. Clarendon&rsquo;s will?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He paused an instant before replying.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Precisely,&rdquo; was his word, as he tapped the table.
    </p>
    <p>
      Isabel smiled, a smile different from that with which she was wont to
      charm. It was one almost of self-contempt, and full of bitter memories.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I had never heard of her,&rdquo; she continued, &ldquo;until I was called upon to
      take her as my own child. Then she was sent to me from people who had had
      the care of her since she was three years old.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Asquith slowly nodded, wrinkling his forehead.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, we will speak no more of that. What I wish to ask you to do for me
      is this:&mdash;Oh, I am ashamed to speak of it! It is something that I
      ought to have done myself already. But I am a coward; I have always been a
      coward. I can&rsquo;t face the consequences of my own&mdash;my own baseness;
      that is the true word. Will you tell Ada Warren what her real position is,
      and what mine?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Asquith raised his head in astonishment.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;She is still ignorant?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I have every reason to believe so. I don&rsquo;t think any one will have told
      her.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Robert bit his upper lip.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Has she never asked questions about her origin?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, but only once. I told her that her parents were friends of Mr.
      Clarendon, and that she was an orphan, therefore I had taken her. That was
      several years ago.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Again there was a pause in the dialogue. Isabel had difficulty in keeping
      her face raised; her cheeks had lost their pallor, the blood every now and
      then made them warm.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;She seems a strange being,&rdquo; Asquith remarked. &ldquo;I am not as a rule tempted
      to puzzle about people&rsquo;s characteristics, but hers provoke one&rsquo;s
      curiosity.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I cannot aid you,&rdquo; Isabel said, speaking quickly. &ldquo;I know her as little
      as on the day when I first saw her. I have tried to be kind; I have tried
      to&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She broke off. Her voice had begun to express emotion, and the sound
      seemed to recall her to self-command. She looked up, smiling more
      naturally, though still with a touch of shame.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Will you help me, cousin?&rdquo; she asked.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Certainly I will do what you wish. Do you desire me to explain everything
      in detail&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The will, the will,&rdquo; she interposed, with a motion of her hand. &ldquo;Yes, the
      full details of the will.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And if she asks me&mdash;&mdash;?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You know nothing&mdash;that is best. You cannot speak to her on such a
      subject. Will you wait for me a moment?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She rose hastily and left the room. Asquith remained standing till her
      return. She was only a few moments absent, and came back with a folded
      paper in her hand.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;This,&rdquo; she said, &ldquo;is a full copy of the will. It might be best to read it
      to her, or even to let her have it to read herself. She may keep it if she
      wishes to.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Asquith took the paper and stood in thought.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You have well considered this?&rdquo; he asked.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, for long enough. I thank you for your great kindness.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;When shall I see her? To-morrow is Sunday. Does she go to church?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Never.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Then I will take the opportunity, whilst you and Miss Meres are away.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Isabel gave him her hand, and they exchanged good-nights.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
