    <h2>
      CHAPTER IV.
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">R</span>obert Asquith was
      in the garden before breakfast next morning, with untroubled countenance,
      scrutinising objects in detail, now and then suppressing a tendency to
      give forth a note or two of song. He walked with his hands in his pockets,
      not removing them when he stooped to examine the gardener&rsquo;s inscription
      stuck by the root of a flower or shrub. He had no special interest in
      these matters, but the bent of his mind was to observation; he avoided as
      much as possible mere ruminativeness. The course of his wandering brought
      him round to the stables; the sight of their admirable order and of the
      beasts in the stalls&mdash;the carriage-horse, the two beautiful ponies
      that Mrs. Clarendon drove, and the five-year-old chestnut which at present
      she rode&mdash;gave him an Englishman&rsquo;s satisfaction. Isabel was as active
      and practical in the superintendence of her stables as in every other
      pursuit which she regarded as duty or pleasure; the most exacting squire
      could not have had things in better condition. Here Robert came in contact
      with his acquaintance, the groom, and received from him much information
      about the animals, also concerning their predecessors in the stables.
      Strolling back to the front lawn, accompanied by the house-dog, he met Ada
      Warren. She wore her ordinary brown straw hat, and seemed to be coming
      from the park. The dog began to leap about her, barking joyously.
    </p>
    <p>
      She spoke a quiet good-morning, but did not offer to shake hands. Robert
      talked a little about the fine weather and the pleasure of breathing
      morning air; he elicited in reply a series of assents. Ada had taken one
      of the dog&rsquo;s silky ears in her hand, and the animal suffered himself very
      patiently to be led thus.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Do you remain at home this morning, Miss Warren?&rdquo; Robert inquired, as
      they approached the house.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;In that case, may I ask if you will favour me with half-an-hour&rsquo;s
      conversation some time after breakfast?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She looked round with frank surprise, only turning away her gaze when she
      had assured herself of his seriousness.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I shall be in the library till one o&rsquo;clock,&rdquo; she said.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Thank you; I will come there.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Watching her at breakfast, Robert thought he perceived some traces of
      curiosity and anticipation in the girl&rsquo;s face; once, too, he caught her
      eyes straying in his direction. &ldquo;Come,&rdquo; he said to himself, &ldquo;there is
      something human in her after all. We shall see if we can&rsquo;t make the
      exhibition yet more pronounced.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      As soon as Mrs. Clarendon and Rhoda Meres were gone to church, Asquith
      made his way to the library, carrying the document which Isabel had
      entrusted to him the night before. The room remained very much as it had
      been in Mr. Clarendon&rsquo;s days. When gentlemen were at Knightswell, it was
      used as a retreat for smoking; Isabel herself scarcely ever entered, but
      Ada Warren used it regularly. There were on the shelves not more than four
      hundred volumes, and half of these were calf-bound legal literature and
      blue-books, representing periods of Mr. Clarendon&rsquo;s career. On the table
      lay volumes of a different kind, many of them showing Mudie&rsquo;s tickets;
      they were works of human interest of the day, food&mdash;or at least
      refreshment&mdash;for an active and independent mind; French and German
      books were here too. Asquith glanced at the names on one or two of the
      yellow backs in passing, and suppressed a smile. But he thought all the
      better of the girl for her intellectual enterprise.
    </p>
    <p>
      Ada sat with her back to the window, reading; at his entrance she closed
      her book, but did not move. He placed a chair at a little distance from
      her, and leaned forward, as if about to talk in a familiar manner.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I surprised you by my request?&rdquo; he began, with a smile. &ldquo;It was rather
      formal, and necessarily so, for it is strictly a matter of business that I
      wish to speak of.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Ada&rsquo;s position had not allowed him to get a clear view of her face at
      first. Raising his eyes after this introduction, he was startled by what
      he saw. The girl was the hue of death; all the natural tint had left her
      cheeks, and her lips were unnaturally pale. She was pressing one hand
      against her left side, and her eyes showed that she was suffering from
      scarcely controllable agitation. He was in doubt whether to take notice of
      it or not, when she suddenly rose from the chair.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You are unwell, Miss Warren&mdash;&mdash;?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She turned sharply away, and walked the length of the room.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Shall I postpone&mdash;this business?&rdquo; said Robert, remarkably interested
      in observing her.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Thank you, no,&rdquo; was her reply, as she seated herself further from him
      than before. &ldquo;I shall be obliged to you if you will speak plainly and
      directly, whatever the business is. I have a headache; a long conversation
      will be disagreeable to me.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I will speak as directly as possible. At Mrs. Clarendon&rsquo;s request I have
      undertaken to make known to you certain facts regarding your&mdash;your
      future, of which, I understand, it has not been deemed necessary to speak
      hitherto. I have, in short, to tell you what were the provisions of the
      late Mr. Clarendon&rsquo;s will; they concern you nearly.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Ada&rsquo;s aspect was calm, but he saw that her bosom rose and fell in a way
      which showed an inward struggle. She gave no sign of a wish to speak.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I have here a copy of the will,&rdquo; he continued, unrolling the paper. &ldquo;It
      is long, and of course full of technicalities. Perhaps I shall do best to
      put the gist of it into a few plain words. To begin then, Mr. Clarendon
      made you heiress of all but the whole of his real and personal estate,
      with possession upon your attainment of your majority, or, should you
      marry before that age, then at your marriage. Under the will two trustees
      are appointed, gentlemen who were Mr. Clarendon&rsquo;s friends&mdash; I need
      not mention their names. Until either of the events which should give you
      possession, Mrs. Clarendon had the use of Knightswell, with all it
      contained, and an income from the estate of two thousand pounds a year;
      this, however, only on condition that she took you into her house and
      brought you up in every way as her own child, with care for your education
      such as the trustees should approve. If Mrs. Clarendon declined to accept
      this condition, or if she married again prior to your entering into
      possession, her benefit by the will was limited to an annuity of three
      hundred pounds.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Robert paused. His tone was as matter-of-fact as if he were demonstrating
      a proposition of Euclid, but a smile had at length risen to his face. It
      came of his observation of the listener. Ada had closed her eyes; her
      hands were nervously clasped upon her lap.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You follow this, Miss Warren?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She raised her lids and regarded him. Her bosom had ceased to heave; she
      seemed to have regained her ordinary state of mind.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I follow it,&rdquo; she said.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Should you die, unmarried, before the end of your twenty-first year,&rdquo;
       Asquith pursued, &ldquo;the whole of the estate goes to certain very remote
      connections of Mr. Clarendon.&mdash;No other contingency is provided for.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No other contingency is provided for,&rdquo; repeated the girl mechanically.
      &ldquo;What do you mean by that?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I mean&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Robert interrupted himself, and resumed in an off-hand way:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, other possible cases which will occur to one thinking the matter
      over.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Ada appeared to reflect. Her face was turned slightly upwards, and a
      restful expression had come upon it.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Is it,&rdquo; she asked at length, &ldquo;within your province to tell me any more
      than this?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I think,&rdquo; Robert replied, &ldquo;that I have nothing more to tell. If you wish
      it, I will leave this copy with you; I understood Mrs. Clarendon to say
      that you might keep it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Thank you, I will do so.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She rose and took it from his hand.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;There is one thing,&rdquo; she said, &ldquo;that I should like to ask you; I dare say
      you will have no objection to answer. Are the provisions of this will
      generally known&mdash;to Mrs. Clarendon&rsquo;s friends, I would say?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;In all probability they are,&rdquo; was his reply.
</p>
    <p>
&ldquo;Thank you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Clearly there was nothing more to be said on either side. Any comment from
      Asquith was of course out of the question, and Ada, at all times so chary
      of her conversation, was not likely to give utterance to her feelings
      under the present circumstances. She moved away, slightly returned the
      other&rsquo;s bow, and went from the room.
    </p>
    <p>
      At luncheon Ada did not appear. It was not an uncommon thing for her to
      take meals by herself; but Mrs. Clarendon and Robert felt that her absence
      to-day had a significance. She was at dinner, however, and behaved as
      usual. Nothing in her betrayed a change in her state of mind.
    </p>
    <p>
      Whilst Rhoda was reading in the garden in the afternoon, Mrs. Clarendon
      strayed apart with her cousin.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You have told her?&rdquo; she said, meeting Robert&rsquo;s look.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, and left the copy of the will with her. It seems to have made her
      oblivious of lunch.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Poor girl!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The exclamation was a sincere one. Robert looked surprised.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Did she ask you many questions?&rdquo; Isabel continued.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Two: whether I had anything more to tell her; and whether I thought that
      the will was generally known? To the former I said &lsquo;No;&rsquo; to the latter
      &lsquo;Yes.&rsquo;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Whether it was generally known,&rdquo; repeated Isabel, with a low laugh of a
      not very mirthful kind. Then, after a pause, &ldquo;What do people say of me?
      What is the common talk about me? What do the men say? and&mdash;oh! the
      women?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;My dear cousin, you know perfectly well what they say; what they have
      been saying since they first began to talk about you&mdash;that you are a
      charming woman, and so good-hearted that no one can for shame breathe a
      word against you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Isabel sighed.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Rather, so shameless that gossip has not yet found the proper term to
      characterise me. Well, never mind myself; happily I shall soon cease to be
      an object of any general interest. But did she not ask any question about
      the value of the property?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No word of it. She kept me strictly at arm&rsquo;s length.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And she displayed no&mdash;no emotion?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;At first, yes; she was extremely agitated. But she held it down. I
      imagine she is what is called a woman of character. I had rather not be
      her husband.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Isabel made no reply, but walked on with her head bent.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Will you let me ask you,&rdquo; Robert began, &ldquo;had you any particular reason
      for wishing to inform her of these matters just now?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, I had. There is no reason why I shouldn&rsquo;t tell you. There is a
      certain Mr. Lacour&mdash;you&rsquo;ll meet him here to-morrow afternoon&mdash;a
      young man whom I have known for some time as a friend of the Bruce Pages;
      their place is at Hanford, five miles off. He&rsquo;s a brother of Sir Miles
      Lacour. Well, Mr. Vincent Lacour has called on me often in town, and a
      week ago he lunched with us here; he&rsquo;s staying at the Bruce Pages&rsquo; again.
      I rather like him, and I believe there&rsquo;s not a bit of harm in him really;
      but he seems to have been terribly wild, and he&rsquo;s quarrelled with his
      brother, the baronet. I don&rsquo;t suppose he&rsquo;s anything left to live on, and
      Sir Miles refuses to help him any more. We learn all this from young
      Lacour himself; he&rsquo;s remarkably frank, embarrassingly so at times. Now I
      half fancy he&rsquo;s made an impression on Ada; certainly I never knew her talk
      so freely with any one, or show such healthy signs of interest. It
      wouldn&rsquo;t be surprising; he&rsquo;s a charming young fellow, decidedly handsome,
      and the strangest talker. I fancied Ada looked pleased when I mentioned
      that he was coming to the garden party tomorrow. I don&rsquo;t know whether he
      ought to be put in the girl&rsquo;s way, but I had to ask the Bruce Pages, and I
      couldn&rsquo;t leave him out very well. Now you see my reason. I have never
      before been obliged to think of such a thing. It would be unjust to Ada to
      leave her in the dark as to her true position.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;This Mr. Lacour is doubtless aware of the circumstances?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Without a doubt.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And you think he might&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It is not impossible. He must be in desperate straits.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;How old is the individual?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;About three-and-twenty, I think. He had ten thousand pounds of his own
      when he came of age.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Wherewith he has purchased experience. He must be rich in that article.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&rsquo;m afraid he is; but I confess I like him. I don&rsquo;t think he would be a
      bad husband. I believe his oats are sown.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I can, of course, have no opinion; but the situation is an interesting
      one.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      They turned about, and walked a stretch of the lawn in silence.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I wish it were over,&rdquo; Isabel said with a sigh. &ldquo;I wish the poor girl had
      a good husband and all were well settled. I am tired of playing the
      farce.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You look forward with&mdash;with equanimity?&rdquo; Robert said hesitatingly,
      with a glance at her face.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;More, with eagerness. I want to throw off a weight. I shall be the
      happiest woman in England.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;On three hundred a year, cousin Isabel?&rdquo; ventured Asquith.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;On three hundred a year, cousin Robert. I wish I had never had more.
      Come, we must go back to Rhoda. Isn&rsquo;t Rhoda a dear?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
