    <h2>
      CHAPTER X.
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">T</span>he rectory was at
      all times open to Kingcote. Mr. Vissian welcomed him as the only man
      within reach who could talk on congenial topics; Mrs. Vissian liked him
      personally, and for the sake of the romantic stories which she wove about
      him in her imagination. To Percy Vissian he had become an object of a
      child&rsquo;s affectionate regard, as well as of the reverence which attaches to
      men of mystery. Percy not infrequently made his way to the cottage, but
      never outlived that fairy-tale sensation with which he had first crossed
      its threshold. That Kingcote lived here absolutely alone, that he passed
      nights in the dread solitude of this ivy-wrapped cell, that he had nothing
      to do but to read the books which contained such deep and wondrous things,
      invested him in the child&rsquo;s eyes with something of the unearthliness of a
      wizard. Anything but a youngster of boisterous instincts, Percy moved
      about in the cottage with the gravest gait; as he never went up the dim,
      narrow staircase, there still remained a portion of the abode of which his
      fancy was free to make what it would, and it often seemed to him that a
      strange light footfall came to his ears from the floor above. He would not
      have ventured to ask about this, which in truth was only the product of
      his excited imagination. When he had tea with his friend everything tasted
      to him quite differently from the flavours of home; the mere bread became
      cake&mdash;he munched dry pieces with a strange relish, and the milk did
      not come from ordinary cows. But his great delight was when, after such a
      meal, he settled himself on his uncomfortable chair and saw Kingcote
      preparing to read to him. Often the reading was of English poetry, and
      that was enjoyable; but better still was when the wizard took down one of
      those books of which the mere character suggested magic lore&mdash;a
      German book, and, turning it into free English, read a tale of Tieck, or
      Musàus, or Grimm, or Bechstein, or Hauff. Then did the child&rsquo;s face glow
      with attention, his features become elf-like with the stirring of
      phantasy; and, when Kingcote ceased, he would move with a deep sigh and
      peer curiously about the room. He would beg to be allowed to look at these
      volumes for himself, touching the pages with delicate finger, spelling
      here and there a word and asking its meaning. There was a book of German
      ballads, plentifully illustrated, and over these pictures the boy was
      never tired of musing. Percy Vissian owed not a little to his friend for
      these afternoons at Wood End.
    </p>
    <p>
      With the elder people Kingcote&rsquo;s intimacy was not one of unrestrained
      confidence, though it only fell short of it by that degree which marks the
      superficiality of most friendships. For instance, he never felt tempted to
      speak to Mrs. Vissian, even after months of familiar intercourse, as he
      had spoken to Isabel Clarendon in their first conversation. The bright
      little woman did not exercise a compelling power upon his inner self, as
      Isabel had already done. There was much mutual kindness between them, and,
      it might be, as nearly a genuine friendship as is possible between man and
      woman; for such association gains in completeness only at the loss of the
      characteristics which justify it for friendship&rsquo;s name. Mrs. Vissian
      showed this supreme wisdom, of never offering sympathy. It was by no means
      always with a conventionally smooth face that Kingcote came into her
      presence; at times he sat in her parlour, a picture of wretchedness, and
      scarcely answered when she spoke to him. For to Kingcote there came more
      of misery than of consolation from the aspect of this gentle peaceful
      home; often enough he was stirred to bitterness by the sight of this
      perfect content, this ideal domesticity, this sweet assuagement of the
      evils of life; the contrast with his own position was not fruitful of
      soothing. When he sat with her in that state of mind Mrs. Vissian seemed
      not to perceive it, or at most uttered a light word about low spirits. Of
      course she thought a good deal about it, but the blessed wisdom of content
      was strong in her, and not even by a look did she display special
      interest.
    </p>
    <p>
      Mr. Vissian himself was amusing. His bibliomania and kindred interests
      never for an instant lost their hold upon him. When Kingcote once asked
      whether he did not at times weary of such things, the rector stared in
      amazement. The study was not the only room in which precious books were
      stored; upstairs was a chamber packed almost solidly with volumes, old and
      new. Mr. Vissian boasted that he knew every book in the mass, and could at
      any time make his way to any he desired to consult; it was only a matter
      of excavation. One slight anxiety his collection cost him; the upper walls
      of the house had begun to show rather large cracks, and it was possible
      that eventually the burden of literature would bring the roof down. But
      that was a risk which must take its place in the ordinary count of human
      contingencies. The rector subscribed to a considerable number of literary
      societies: the &ldquo;Shakspere,&rdquo; the &ldquo;Chaucer,&rdquo; the &ldquo;Early English Text,&rdquo; and
      others of the kind, receiving their publications and having them duly
      bound for a place on shelves in some commodious dwelling of the future. In
      the course of talk over such things, Kingcote was by chance enlightened as
      to the meaning of that little incident which had struck him in his very
      first interview with Mr. Vissian&mdash;the latter&rsquo;s momentary doubt, or
      seeming doubt, whether he could produce the money which was requested.
      Kingcote discovered that his friend lived in perpetual pecuniary
      embarrassment. Mrs. Vissian exercised control over her husband&rsquo;s
      expenditure to the point of preventing its exceeding their income, but
      that was all. The quarterly cheque was invariably demanded by outstanding
      liabilities as soon as it arrived, and unfortunately the cheque was not a
      very large one. It often happened that neither the rector nor his wife had
      half a sovereign in the world, a singular state of things in so otherwise
      orderly a household. In lending Kingcote that sovereign they had just then
      left themselves literally penniless. Fortunately the cheque was due. Mrs.
      Vissian dreaded the arrival of a booksellers second-hand catalogue;
      whenever it was possible, she intercepted all such, and mercilessly
      committed them to the flames. Yet the subject never occasioned a moment&rsquo;s
      trouble between husband and wife; Mr. Vissian pursued his course in
      calmness. He was working (as a volunteer, of course) for a great English
      dictionary, which a certain society had it in view to produce. Also, he
      had taken up the new ideas of textual criticism in Elizabethan literature,
      and spent hours in counting the syllables in each line of a scene of this
      or the other dramatist. Though such a placid little man, he revelled in
      literary horrors. It delighted him to read aloud ghastly scenes from
      Webster, dwelling with gusto on the forceful utterances. Withal his
      orthodoxy was unimpeachable, it never occurred to him to carry his
      criticism into Biblical spheres. To please him, Kingcote now and then
      attended his services; naturally there was no further discussion on
      religious topics between the two.
    </p>
    <p>
      As October drew on, and evenings began to be dark and cold, the comfort of
      Mr. Vissian&rsquo;s study and of his wife&rsquo;s sitting-room assuredly lost nothing
      in the eyes of the hermit of Wood End, yet his visits became less
      frequent. He presented himself, however, about nine o&rsquo;clock one night, and
      was received by Mrs. Vissian with the usual friendliness. The rector was
      expected home every moment.
    </p>
    <p>
      It had been raining all day, and the temperature justified the first fire,
      which crackled merrily and made the bright little room look cheerier than
      ever. The table was laid for supper (the Vissians dined at one o&rsquo;clock)
      and a pleasant odour as of toasted cheese took advantage of the door being
      ajar to creep insidiously about the room. Mrs. Vissian sat with her feet
      on a stool, mending a pair of Percy&rsquo;s stockings.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You look tired,&rdquo; she said, as Kingcote sat in silence and watched her out
      of half-closed eyes.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am, a little. I have been walking.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But in this dreadful rain?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Has it rained? I don&rsquo;t think I noticed it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Mrs. Vissian regarded him for an instant with surprise, then laughed a
      little, and bent over her work. Her left hand and arm were thrust into the
      stocking, and she held her head sideways, observing the growth of her
      darning with a kind of artistic earnestness and pleasure. A small black
      cat, which had just come in licking its mouth, put its fore feet on to the
      stool and looked up into its mistress&rsquo;s face. The fire crackled, and a
      sound of clattered plates came from the kitchen. Then was heard another
      sound, that of the rector&rsquo;s latch-key at the front door. Mrs. Vissian
      quickly put down her work, and, with a bright look, went from the room.
    </p>
    <p>
      Kingcote gripped the arm of his chair and uttered a low moan.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ha, well met!&rdquo; exclaimed the rector, as, after divesting himself of a wet
      overcoat, he entered, flicking his black trousers with his handkerchief
      and dubiously regarding his boots. His cheeks, as always, were aglow with
      health and spirits; on his whiskers gleamed drops of rain. He stood with
      his back to the fire, and passed his finger round between collar and neck,
      a habit of his which always seemed to give him ease. &ldquo;I have a message for
      you&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The servant entered with a tray of savoury viands. The rector broke off in
      his speech to regard the goods which the gods were providing; he did so
      with a critical, yet a satisfied, eye.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;A message for <i>me?</i>&rdquo; Kingcote asked indifferently.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ha, yes!&rdquo; Mr. Vissian had been led off into a different train of thought,
      it seemed.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Mrs. Clarendon wants you to go to see her.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Indeed!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Where did you meet her, dear?&rdquo; Mrs. Vissian inquired, as she bundled away
      her work in preparation for the meal.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;She&rsquo;s going to sit through the night with Mrs. Stigard. I shall be
      surprised if the poor old woman lives till morning; ten to one I shall be
      sent for. Lucy,&rdquo; he added, as if a semi-conscious process of reflection
      had just come to clear issue in his mind, &ldquo;that parcel for the binder is
      still lying upstairs. I saw it this morning with amazement; thought it had
      gone a week ago.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&rsquo;ll see to it, dear,&rdquo; replied his wife, without looking up from the
      bread she was cutting. &ldquo;Pity it has been forgotten.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Forgotten! And you, who never forget anything!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Then, turning to Kingcote, he declaimed, with humorous gesture and
      emphasis:
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      &ldquo;Brother Cosroe, I find myself aggrieved,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Yet insufficient to express the same,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      For it requires a great and thundering speech!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;By-the-bye,&rdquo; he continued, as he poured out a glass of ale from the
      foam-capped jug, &ldquo;it&rsquo;s beyond all doubt that Grubb is wrong in his
      calculation. He says, you remember, that the proportion of unstopt lines
      in the &lsquo;Two Gentlemen&rsquo; is one in eleven. Now I make it one in nine decimal
      fifteen, and I&rsquo;ve been over it twice with the utmost care. This is a point
      of considerable importance. Take that chair, Kingcote.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Thank you,&rdquo; Kingcote said, &ldquo;I shall not eat.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why not? There&rsquo;s pippins and cheese to come. Then, at least, as Claudius
      said to the chickens, drink.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Kingcote declined, in spite of much hospitable pressure, and kept his
      arm-chair. Mr. Vissian applying himself to his supper, talked in intervals
      of mastication.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Mrs. Clarendon wishes you to call tomorrow or next day; pray do so. I
      can&rsquo;t quite make out that mistake of Grubb&rsquo;s; he must have calculated from
      an edition in which the lines are differently arranged. I shall
      communicate with him. Lucy, my love, I beg of you to see that those books
      are dispatched the first thing to-morrow; the dilatory scoundrel always
      keeps me waiting, and there&rsquo;s a &lsquo;Cursor Mundi&rsquo; I want to work at.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Kingcote suddenly rose and stepped to Mrs. Vissian to bid her good night.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Going, what?&rdquo; exclaimed the rector, turning round, with an end of his
      napkin in each hand. &ldquo;But I wanted to ask your opinion about&mdash;&mdash;
      You don&rsquo;t look well, my dear fellow; what is it?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nothing, nothing. I&rsquo;ve tired myself with walking. I&rsquo;ll get home.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You have an umbrella? Then you must take one of mine. But, I tell you,
      you must; it&rsquo;s raining like a waterspout. Shall I walk with you?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Kingcote had gone off into the darkness with inaudible replies.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What is the matter with him?&rdquo; asked the rector, standing in surprise. &ldquo;Is
      he going to be ill? An awkward look-out in that cottage, with not a soul
      near.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He was very strange when he came,&rdquo; Mrs. Vissian remarked. &ldquo;He said he&rsquo;d
      been walking, and yet wasn&rsquo;t aware that it had rained.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Wasn&rsquo;t aware? Curious fellow, Kingcote.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t you think, Walter, there&rsquo;s something about him we don&rsquo;t understand&mdash;something
      in the circumstances of his life, I mean?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;A good deal. But he&rsquo;s a thoroughly good fellow; I must look in at Wood
      End the first thing in the morning.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      They resumed their seats.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Lucy,&rdquo; observed the rector, &ldquo;you are blooming to-night! Upon my word,
      every year makes you younger and more beautiful.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What makes you think of such a thing just now?&rdquo; asked the other, laughing
      as she shook her head.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t know. I suppose half the joy of happiness comes of contrast with
      others&rsquo; less fortunate lot.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, I don&rsquo;t like to think that, Walter,&rdquo; protested the wife rather sadly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Many things are true, my dear, which we don&rsquo;t like to think.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Lucy moved to reach something, and took the occasion to kiss her husband&rsquo;s
      forehead.
    </p>
    <p>
      And Kingcote, plodding through the lane&rsquo;s mud, reached his door. The old
      oak-stump in front of the cottage stood like a night-fear; the copse
      behind, all but stripped of leaves, gave forth dismal whisperings; rain
      beat hard upon the roof-thatch. The tenant took the key from his pocket
      and entered the cold room; he could not see his hands. Without seeking any
      light he felt his way up the crazy stairs, and lay down to such rest as he
      might find.
    </p>
    <p>
      It rained till noon of the following day, then began to clear. When a
      couple of hours of pale sunshine had half dried the hedges, Kingcote set
      forth to walk to Knightswell. Mr. Vissian had been as good as his word in
      calling.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, nothing; a headache,&rdquo; was the answer he received to his anxious
      inquiries. &ldquo;I hope I wasn&rsquo;t more than usually ill-mannered; pray ask Mrs.
      Vissian to try and tolerate me.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You&rsquo;re getting a little low, it strikes me; too much solitude.
      By-the-bye, you&rsquo;ll look in at Knightswell this afternoon?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I suppose Mrs. Clarendon feels obliged to ask me; I dare say she&rsquo;d rather
      I kept away.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;My dear sir, these are outcomes of the black humour; you are not
      yourself. Mrs. Clarendon will be very glad indeed to see you; so she
      assured me. I pray you, fight against this tendency to melancholia.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      It was difficult to reach the gates without having previously collected
      considerably more mud than one cares to convey into a lady&rsquo;s drawing-room.
      Kingcote endeavoured to remove some of this superfluous earth as he walked
      up the drive by rubbing his boots in the wet grass; the result was not
      inspiriting.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Pooh!&rdquo; he exclaimed impatiently. &ldquo;If she really cares to see me, she
      won&rsquo;t regard the state of my boots; any one who accepts such as I am, must
      take mud and all.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The thought appeared to amuse him, he walked on with a laugh.
    </p>
    <p>
      As he entered the garden, he met the trap just driving away from the
      house. A gentleman was seated in it. He had rather the look of a man of
      business, and was reading a letter. He scanned Kingcote, then resumed his
      reading.
    </p>
    <p>
      Disturbed with the thought that there might be other visitors in the
      house, Kingcote hesitated, doubted whether to go on. He made up his mind
      to do so, however, not without sundry fresh communings with himself of a
      bitter kind. On inquiry he found that Mrs. Clarendon was at home, and,
      after a moment in the hall, he was led to the dining-room. Mrs. Clarendon
      was writing letters at a table by the window; as she rose, he thought he
      detected annoyance on her face.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I fear I disturb you,&rdquo; he said coldly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You don&rsquo;t at all; or rather, you will not, if you&rsquo;ll let me treat you as
      a friend. I have just one letter I am obliged to write; I asked the
      servant to bring you here, thinking you might like to look at the pictures
      till I have done. One or two are thought good, I believe&mdash;that
      Veronese, and that Ruysdael, and the Greuze yonder. May I?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      It was hard not to smile in reply to her voice and look as she spoke the
      last two little words, the more so that it was clear she had something
      just now to trouble her quite other than the inopportune arrival of a
      visitor. Kingcote walked to the picture she had indicated as a Veronese,
      and, affecting to view it, let his eyes wander to Isabel at the
      writing-table. She was thinking, previous to commencing her letter. Her
      left arm rested on the desk, and the thumb and middle finger of the hand
      pressed her forehead; with the end of the penholder she tapped her chin.
      He noticed how beautiful was the outline of her head, relieved against the
      bright window; noticed, too, the grace of her neck when she bent forward
      to write. The scratching of her pen&mdash;she wrote very rapidly&mdash;was
      the only sound in the room.
    </p>
    <p>
      Kingcote went from picture to picture, his mind not quite tuned to judge
      and enjoy their merits. One, however, held him. When lunching here, he had
      sat with his back to the wall of which this canvas was the central
      ornament, so had not observed it. It was a portrait of Mrs. Clarendon,
      painted probably at the time of her marriage, an excellent picture. As he
      gazed at it, Isabel came forward.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Do you recognise it?&rdquo; she asked, tapping on one hand with the letter she
      held in the other.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Without doubt.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And moralise? But,&rdquo; she added quickly, &ldquo;I want you to look at this
      child&rsquo;s head. Isn&rsquo;t it exquisitely sweet?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      His eyes wandered back to the portrait, and, on their way to the door, he
      again paused before it.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Did I show you my ferns the last time you were here?&rdquo; Isabel asked. &ldquo;Will
      you walk so far?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She led to the rear of the hall, thence, by a glass door, into a short
      glass-roofed passage, the door at the end of which opened into the
      conservatory. The first section was a small rotunda, twenty feet in
      diameter and twelve feet high. The floor was of unglazed tiles, the
      ceiling of ornamental stucco; round the wall was a broad cushioned seat,
      above which, commencing at a height of some four feet from the ground,
      were windows of richly coloured glass, pictured with leaves and flowers
      and fruit. A stand for plants occupied the centre, but at present the
      shelves were almost bare.
    </p>
    <p>
      Mrs. Clarendon threw back one of the windows.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;There is a good view from here,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;A tree used to intercept it,
      but we had it cut down in the spring to clear a piece of ground for
      tennis.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      From the hill, on which the house was built, a broad stretch of green park
      led the eye to a considerable distance in the direction of Salcot. The
      roof of the cottage at Wood End was just visible. Kingcote drew attention
      to it.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t see any smoke from the chimney,&rdquo; Mrs. Clarendon remarked, with a
      pleasant glance. &ldquo;It is to be hoped you keep good fires this damp weather.
      Is the place rainproof? These last two days will have tested it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It seems to be sound.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And you still find it your ideal?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The cottage? I did not choose it as an ideal abode.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But the quietness, the retirement, I mean. In that, at all events, you
      have not been disappointed.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Certainly not.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Isabel shuddered.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;How you live there I can&rsquo;t understand. But I suppose you find it best for
      your studies.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t study,&rdquo; returned Kingcote, rather vacantly, looking at the
      pictured glass of the window.
    </p>
    <p>
      Isabel closed the window and passed to the next door.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am so sorry Miss Warren is not at home,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;I quite thought she
      would be, but at the last moment she decided to go to London to see
      something in the South Kensington Museum&mdash;oh, Schliemann&rsquo;s
      discoveries!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Does Miss Warren read Greek and Latin?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Latin she does, and is just beginning Greek. She&rsquo;s a wonderfully clever
      girl, but it&rsquo;s difficult to get her to talk. I am sure you will find her
      interesting when you have had opportunities of talking with her.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      They were now in an ordinary hot-house. Isabel pointed out the plants
      which interested her.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I have just had a visit from my lawyer,&rdquo; she said, as she plucked away
      some dead leaves. &ldquo;What tedious people lawyers are, and so dreadfully
      indispensable.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I suppose I passed him on the drive.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No doubt. But I mustn&rsquo;t speak ill of the good man; he came all the way
      from London to save me a journey.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      They moved about for a few moments in silence.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;There&rsquo;s nothing here to look at, really,&rdquo; Mrs. Clarendon said. &ldquo;If I
      could afford it I should have the place kept in good order; but I can&rsquo;t.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She did not appear to notice the look of surprise which Kingcote was for a
      moment unable to suppress. Leading the way back to the rotunda, she placed
      a loose cushion and seated herself. The warmth here was temperate, not
      more than the season required for comfort.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;So you don&rsquo;t study?&rdquo; she began, with friendly abruptness, when she had
      pointed to a place for her companion. &ldquo;What, then, do you do? I am rude,
      you see, but&mdash;I wish to know.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I wish I could satisfactorily account for my days. I read a little, walk
      a good deal, see the Vissians now and then&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And cultivate <i>ennui</i>&mdash;-isn&rsquo;t it so? A most unprofitable kind
      of gardening. I believe you are thoroughly miserable; in fact, you are not
      at much pains to hide it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Scarcely as much as courtesy requires, you would say. I wish I could be
      more amusing, Mrs. Clarendon.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t ask you to be amusing&mdash;only to show yourself a little amused
      at my impertinent curiosity. Why should you have so forgotten the habit of
      cheerfulness?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The habit?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Certainly. Is it not a habit, as long as we are in health?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;In people happily endowed, I suppose. Temperament and circumstances may
      enable one to keep a bright view of life.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Rather, a reasonable effort of the will, I should say. I am often tempted
      to be dreary, but I refuse to give way.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Kingcote smiled, almost laughed.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You think I have nothing to be dreary about?&rdquo; she asked, gazing at him as
      if trying to read his thoughts. &ldquo;That is a mistake; I don&rsquo;t speak idly. It
      would be excusable enough if I lost my cheerfulness. But with me it <i>is</i>
      a habit. Under any circumstances there&rsquo;s a great deal of entertainment to
      be got out of life. Of course, if one puts oneself under the most
      unfavourable conditions&mdash;goes to live in a remote hermitage, shuts
      oneself from social comforts, reads doleful books about funeral urns&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She caught his eye, and broke off with bright laughter.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You don&rsquo;t care for Sir Thomas Browne?&rdquo; he asked.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I shouldn&rsquo;t be honest if I said I did. I am afraid that kind of reading
      is beyond me. Ada&mdash;Miss Warren&mdash;enjoys it; but she is
      intellectual, and I cannot pretend to be.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What do you read, Mrs. Clarendon?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The newspapers, and now and then a novel&mdash;<i>voilà tout!</i>&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;There are better things than books,&rdquo; observed Kingcote.
    </p>
    <p>
      A footstep was heard in the inner house.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Is that you, Reuben?&rdquo; the lady called, causing the gardener to put his
      head through the door with the admission, &ldquo;It be me, ma&rsquo;am.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She exchanged words with him, then proposed to Kingcote that they should
      go to the drawing-room for tea. On their way she paused in the hall, with
      talk about the panelling. Pointing to a fox&rsquo;s head:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;A trophy of last season. We killed, that day, a couple of fields behind
      Wood End.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Tea appeared in a few minutes. As Isabel poured out two cups, her guest
      made a feint of closely examining a framed photograph of Knightswell,
      which stood on the table. He was less at his ease than on the tiled floor
      of the conservatory; the dried mud upon his boots showed brutally against
      the dark carpet, disposing him to savage humorousness. He became aware
      that the beverage was silently held out to him. Her own cup in hand, Mrs.
      Clarendon reclined in her chair, and gradually her eyes fixed themselves
      upon him. He was conscious of the look before he returned it, and,
      speaking at length, did so as if in reply to a question, though himself
      interrogative.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Did you ever visit a London hospital?&rdquo; Isabel manifested no surprise; her
      face had even a quiet smile of satisfaction.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes,&rdquo; she answered. &ldquo;I once went to see a servant in St. Thomas&rsquo;s.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ah, I was studying there&mdash;let me see, six years ago. My father was a
      medical man, and determined that I should be the same. At his death I gave
      it up; I hadn&rsquo;t finished my course.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It was not to your taste?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I loathed it. My bad dreams are still of hospital wards and
      dissecting-rooms. I cannot bear to see the word &lsquo;hospital&rsquo; in print. The
      experience of those years has poisoned my life, as thoroughly as a slip of
      the lancet would have poisoned my blood.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Had you that dislike from the commencement?&rdquo; Isabel asked, after putting
      down her empty cup, and crossing her hands on her lap with an air of
      attention.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, not in the same degree. I thought this profession would do as well as
      another. I believe I even had philanthropic glows now and then, and
      perhaps even a period of scientific interest. The latter did not survive
      the steps from theory to practice; the former&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He made a motion with his hand, and smiled.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The very last thing I should ever have associated with you,&rdquo; remarked
      Isabel, with puzzled thoughtfulness.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;A philanthropic zeal?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I didn&rsquo;t mean that, but I am not sure that I mayn&rsquo;t include it. Please go
      on.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Kingcote was resting his forehead on his palm; he resumed without raising
      his eyes.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;My father practised at Norwich&mdash;by-the-bye, our friend, Sir Thomas
      Browne&rsquo;s city. When he died, I went to live with my mother for a while; my
      sister had just married and gone to London, and a sister of my fathers
      shared our house. I thought of all sorts of things&mdash;law, literature
      (of course), even commerce. For I had a small capital&mdash;some shares in
      a joint-stock bank; they gave me a sufficient income, and I could realise
      when I needed. For a year I made plans; then of a sudden I found myself in
      Paris. You know the Continent?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I was in the Riviera for a month, some years ago,&rdquo; Isabel answered,
      without interest. &ldquo;I can&rsquo;t afford to go abroad now.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      It was the second time she had used this phrase. Kingcote watched her
      countenance.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What took you to Paris?&rdquo; she inquired, ignoring the diversion.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nothing. I was turning over an old Bradshaw, and details of the journey
      caught my eye. Next morning I left Norwich. I was abroad two years.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;In France all the time?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No. France, Germany, Switzerland, Italy. Perhaps I saw the countries all
      the better for the necessity I was under of travelling very cheaply&mdash;so
      cheaply, indeed, I wonder how I did it. I walked oftener than rode, and
      dispensed with hotel dinners whenever possible. I have a diary of the two
      years&rsquo; travel.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You will let me read that?&rdquo; Isabel asked quietly.
    </p>
    <p>
      He hesitated; his eyes fixed absently on the windows.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, I will let you read it. It is foolish, boyish; I dare not read it
      myself.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;For what reason?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Because there is nothing I hold more in horror than the ghost of my
      former self. I deny identity,&rdquo; he added with sudden bitterness. &ldquo;How can
      one be held responsible for the thoughts and acts of the being who bore
      his name years ago? The past is no part of our existing self; we are free
      of it, it is buried. That release is the pay Time owes us for doing his
      work.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Isabel regarded him earnestly; her cheek gathered a warmer hue for a
      moment.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You may read it if you care to,&rdquo; he resumed, falling back to calmness.
      &ldquo;There is no one else to whom I would show it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Isabel waited for him to continue. He sat, bent forward, his hands about
      one knee.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And you returned to England with plans?&rdquo; she asked at length, finding him
      persevere in silence.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, only with experience. I came back because I had news of my mothers
      illness. She was dead and buried before I got home.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It strikes me as curious,&rdquo; he resumed rapidly, &ldquo;that my childhood,
      boyhood in fact, has utterly gone from my memory. I suppose that is why I
      have such slight sympathy with children. I have often tried desperately to
      recover the consciousness of my young days: it has gone. My father, my
      mother, I cannot, recall their relations to me, nor mine to them. Nay,
      facts even have left my memory. I know scarcely anything before the
      beginning of my student years, and even those are vanishing, I find. I
      live only in the present.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But the future?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, from looking forward I shrink as much as from looking back.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      There was another silence.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But since you returned to England?&rdquo; Isabel inquired, &ldquo;have you never
      thought of another profession?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Kingcote laughed.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I had crazy projects for studying art. Gabriel put that into my head. But
      my zeal did not last. It is the same in everything; I lack persistence.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And you have&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Done nothing, you would say,&rdquo; Kingcote supplied in the pause she made.
      &ldquo;Literally nothing; wasted my time, lost my best years. The necessary
      consequence of being made up of <i>wants</i>, without the powers which
      could satisfy them. At present I am engaged in the first work I have done
      for years.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;At last, then!&rdquo; Isabel exclaimed.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, the work of resigning myself to being nothing, of casting off the
      last foolish flattery of self-conceit, of resolutely bidding myself
      understand that fate will bear any amount of idle fuming and remain
      unchanged. It is a task which has its difficulties; rather harder, on the
      whole, than the realisation of death. Did you ever force yourself to
      realise death, not to admit it in idle words, but to&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Isabel motioned him to silence; her face was darkened with a look of pain,
      of fear.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Forgive me,&rdquo; he said in a lower voice; &ldquo;to me it is such a familiar
      thought. I talk so seldom that I forget the difference between reflection
      and conversation.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She spent a moment in clearing her mind of the disturbing thought&mdash;it
      seemed strangely disturbing, and at length banished it with the laugh
      occasioned by a new idea.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I wonder,&rdquo; she said, changing her attitude, &ldquo;what you&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You were going to say&mdash;&mdash;?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You spoke of having thought of commerce. Suppose you had become a man of
      business, and had made your fortune, what would your views of life be?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Who can say? To begin with, I should only have ruined myself; no fortune
      would ever have come in that way. Conceiving that it had, why I should not
      be the same person that I am. Circumstances are the mould which give shape
      to such metal as we happen to be made of. The metal is the same always,
      but it may be cast for mean or for noble uses.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I do not think,&rdquo; Isabel said with gentle reassurance, &ldquo;that Fate uses the
      nobler metals, for mean service; it has abundance of the poorer stuff at
      hand.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That is very well said; if I dared apply it to myself I might yet live
      awhile in the old fools paradise. But there is one gain which saves my
      past years from utter vanity&mdash;I have learnt to know myself.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Have you?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Kingcote smiled.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You say that sadly. Yes, you are quite right. Self-knowledge, in my case,
      is equivalent to disillusion, loss of hope.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I meant nothing of the kind,&rdquo; she rejoined, after reflecting a moment on
      the intention of his words, which she had not at first quite caught. &ldquo;I
      doubt whether you do know yourself. If you did, you would have more
      confidence.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That is the kindness natural to you. But,&rdquo; he added, softening the words
      by his tone, &ldquo;you do not know me.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No&mdash;not yet. It is not easy to know you. I cannot judge you by other
      people.&rdquo; Kingcote rose and walked to the fireplace; Mrs. Clarendon watched
      him, but kept her seat.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You know many people,&rdquo; he said, speaking with his peculiar abruptness,
      which was quite different from the tone of mere familiarity, seemed indeed
      rather to accentuate the distance between them.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Many,&rdquo; Isabel returned, &ldquo;in a way.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It must be strange to have so many acquaintances. It gives you the sense
      of belonging to the world; you do not stand on the outside and look on.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;In a theatre&mdash;watching from an uncomfortable back seat? The stage is
      open to you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And the parts? Even if I were cast, think of my poor memory. The words
      are so hard, so artificial. At most I could play the walking gentleman,
      and in truth I have no mind for that.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Isabel smiled, as if involuntarily, and, after glancing round the room,
      quitted her seat.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;A friend is coming in a day or two to stay with me,&rdquo; she said; &ldquo;not a
      mere acquaintance, but really a friend. I should like you to meet her: you
      won&rsquo;t refuse?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He looked at her and hesitated.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You can&rsquo;t help liking Mrs. Stratton. She has been my nearest friend for
      years.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I may be gone,&rdquo; Kingcote said, in a matter-of-fact tone.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Gone? But you have no intention of leaving?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, a half-intention.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;To return to London?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I suppose so.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She kept silence, and he added:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;My sister&rsquo;s husband is ill. Circumstances might compel me to return.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But you are not summoned? You won&rsquo;t leave your cottage unless there is a
      necessity?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Perhaps not; yet I can&rsquo;t be sure. I act very much on impulse.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That phrase reminds me of some one&mdash;a very foolish young man, whom
      you don&rsquo;t at all resemble.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Some one you know?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;One of the many; never mind him. But you will not be gone before next
      Wednesday; that we may take for granted; unless, of course, you have bad
      news. You will come and lunch with us on Wednesday?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;With yourself and Mrs. Stratton?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And Miss Warren. I want you to know her better.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, I will come, if I am still at Wood End.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He held his hand to take leave. Isabel retained it as she spoke.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;In any case you will not go without coming to say good-bye?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I could not easily do that, Mrs. Clarendon.&rdquo; She went with him into the
      hall, and, when he had left the house, watched him from the drawing-room
      windows till the trees intervened.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
